Weimar and Nazi regimes, and especially their effects on the individual. His portrayals of the lives of refugees from Nazi Germany are especially vivid. His themes are universal, dealing with human relationships, with love in particular, and with the provisional nature of life. Often seen as a one-novel writer due to the immense success of All Quiet onthe Western Front, Remarque wrote many other novels, major works that have nearly all been filmed and have remained popular. Nor should it be ignored that his works are above all else immensely readable: not a negligible criterion. This new study of Remarque's novels treats them as a chronicle of the century, but also looks at them as works that go beyond the reflection of historical events. Brian Murdoch is Emeritus Professor of German atthe University of Stirling, Scotland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aBlack American Experience.  aCinematic Representation.  aErich Maria Remarque.  aLiterary Adaptations.  aLove.  aNazi Regimes.  aOne-Novel Writer.  aPopular Literature.  aProvisional Nature of Life.  aRefugees.  aTwentieth Century.  aWeimar.  aWorld Wars.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781571136770?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571136770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571136770/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles